DE EXCEPTIONIBUS.

Ι have made you solemnly promise to pay me a sum of money, as a preliminary to my advancing you the money, and then never advanced it, · Ι can sue you for the money, for you are bound by the promise, but it would be iniquitous that you should be compelled to fulfil such a promise, and therefore you are permitted to impeach my claim by the exception of Fraud. Or if I agreed not to demand a debt, my right to sue the debtor continues unimpaired, because formless agree ment cannot extinguish civil obli- gationS, but my action would be defeated by an exception alleging the agreement.

ξ 117. Real actions also admit of exceptions3 for instance, if by threats of violence or by fraud you drove or seduced me to grant a thing to you by mancipation3 if you sue me for it, Ι am allowed to plead intimidation or fraud, and if Ι prove it, defeat your claim; or if you knew an estate was a subject of litigation, and bought it of a per- son not in possession, when you claim it of a person in possession you are defeated by an exception.
